<HEADLINE>
MAC WOULD BE GLAD TO SEE LEGISLATIVE SPEAKER VISIT CHINA
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei, March 2 (CNA) 03/02/07  21:57:50 (By Han Nai-kuo)
</P>
<P>
The Mainland Affairs Council (MAC) under the Cabinet would be
glad to see Legislative Speaker Wang Jin-pyng visit China under
the four conditions set by himself, the vice chairman of the MAC
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Liu Te-hsun told a press conference that Wang's trip to China
would have positive effects on cross-Taiwan Strait relations if
he could visit China provided that the visit is necessary for the
country, agreed to by the people, approved by the legislature and
is undertaken on a basis of mutual respect and dignity.
</P>
<P>
Liu made the remarks when asked to comment on media speculation
that Wang will soon visit China.
</P>
<P>
Liu said the MAC would set no hurdles or add other preconditions
to Wang's planned visit.
</P>
<P>
The MAC vice chairman expressed the belief that a visit to China
by the speaker of the nation's highest law-making body would have
positive effects on relations between Taiwan and China.
</P>
<P>
The MAC is the highest government agency responsible for the
planning, development, and implementation of Taiwan's policies
toward China.
</P>
